 Americans who want cheap equipment against those who want to make it</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Kelsey Tamborrino, Benjamin Storrow, E&E News</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/new-pollution-regulations-could-largely-eliminate-coal-power-by-the-2030s/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Pollution"><img alt="Coal power plant with chimney with grey smoke billowing in landscape with trees." class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/4ec9e22c5d204d53/original/GettyImages-1126792043.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Pollution</span> <!-- -->April 25, 2024</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>New Pollution Regulations Could Largely Eliminate Coal Power by the 2030s</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>The EPA has released four new pollution rules, most focusing on coal-fired power, as the final pieces of Biden&rsquo;s push to clean up the power sector</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Jean Chemnick, E&E News</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/how-temperate-forests-could-help-limit-climate-change/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Climate Change"><img alt="Blue Ridge Mountains at sunrise" class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/58c1797e7a13d33b/original/GettyImages-981339856.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Opinion</span> <!-- -->April 25, 2024</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>How Temperate Forests Could Help Limit Climate Change</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>People understand how saving tropical forests is good for the planet, but temperate forests are equally indispensable in fighting climate change</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Amanda Leland, Steven Hamburg</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/how-to-filter-out-harmful-forever-chemicals-at-home/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Pollution"><img alt="Woman&#x27;s hand filling a glass with water at kitchen sink." class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/36e884a7ab948aac/original/GettyImages-1445381865.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Pollution</span> <!-- -->April 25, 2024</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>How to Filter Out Harmful &lsquo;Forever Chemicals&rsquo; at Home</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>An environmental engineer provides a glimpse of the magnitude of the challenge to remove PFAS from water supplies and ways you can reduce these &ldquo;forever chemicals&rdquo; in your own drinking water</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Kyle Doudrick, The Conversation US</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/new-geothermal-technology-could-expand-clean-power-generation/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Climate Change"><img alt="Vapour rises from cooling towers in the separation station at the Nesjavellir Geothermal power station." class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/5ad21db55ca09492/original/GettyImages-607692382-1.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Climate Change</span> <!-- -->April 24, 2024</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>New Geothermal Technology Could Expand Clean Power Generation</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>Long confined to regions with volcanic activity, geothermal promises to become a much more versatile energy source thanks to new technologies</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Katarina Zimmer, Knowable Magazine</p></section></article></div></div><div class="paginationContainer-Dir8D"><a class="paginationButton-Q-Ffv" href="?page=2">Next</a></div><footer class="footer-VfsmT"><div class="footerContainer-pfbjC"><h2 class="footerMainText-wQ3og">Expand Your World with Science</h2></div><div class="footerFlexContainer-XKe5g footerContainer-pfbjC"><div class="footerLinks-m1THn"><p class="footerText-PzHcy">Learn and share the most exciting discoveries, innovations and ideas shaping our world today.</p><a class="footerLink-uRzI4" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/getsciam/">Subscribe</a><a class="footerLink-uRzI4" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/newsletter-signup/">Sign up for our newsletters</a><a class="footerLink-uRzI4" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/">See the latest stories</a><a class="footerLink-uRzI4" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/latest-issue/">Read the latest issue</a><a class="footerLink-uRzI4" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/getsciam/gift/">Give a Gift Subscription</a><p class="footerSocialMedia-7KIIV">Follow Us:<a href="https://www.instagram.com/scientific_american/?hl=en" alt="Instagram link" title="Instagram"><svg class="footerSocialIcon-UQyIx" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 448 512"><path d="M224.1 141c-63.6 0-114.9 51.3-114.9 114.9s51.3 114.9 114.9 114.9S339 319.5 339 255.9 287.7 141 224.1 141zm0 189.6c-41.1 0-74.7-33.5-74.7-74.7s33.5-74.7 74.7-74.7 74.7 33.5 74.7 74.7-33.6 74.7-74.7 74.7zm146.4-194.3c0 14.9-12 26.8-26.8 26.8-14.9 0-26.8-12-26.8-26.8s12-26.8 26.8-26.8 26.8 12 26.8 26.8zm76.1 27.2c-1.7-35.9-9.9-67.7-36.2-93.9-26.2-26.2-58-34.4-93.9-36.2-37-2.1-147.9-2.1-184.9 0-35.8 1.7-67.6 9.9-93.9 36.1s-34.4 58-3